04137nam a22005415i 9780520925892DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209258927 a10.1525/97805209258922doi  a(DE-B1597)647880  a(OCoLC)55891210  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0041902bisacsh1 aBowditch, Phebe Lowell, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHorace and the Gift Economy of Patronage /cPhebe Lowell Bowditch; ed. by Phebe Lowell Bowditch. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aClassics and Contemporary Thought00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Translation -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Gift Economy of Patronage -- t2. Tragic History, Lyric Expiation, and the Gift of Sacrifice -- t3. The Gifts of the Golden Age: Land, Debt, and Aesthetic Surplus -- t4. From Patron to Friend: Epistolary Refashioning and the Economics of Refusal -- t5. The Epistolary Farm and the Status Implications of Epicurean Ataraxia -- tConclusion: The Gift and the Reading Community -- tReferences -- tSubject Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis innovative study explores selected odes and epistles by the late-first-century poet Horace in light of modern anthropological and literary theory. Phebe Lowell Bowditch looks in particular at how the relationship between Horace and his patron Maecenas is reflected in these poems' themes and rhetorical figures. Using anthropological studies on gift exchange, she uncovers an implicit economic dynamic in these poems and skillfully challenges standard views on literary patronage in this period. Horace and the Gift Economy of Patronage provides a striking new understanding of Horace's poems and the Roman system of patronage, and also demonstrates the relevance of New Historicist and Marxist critical paradigms for Roman studies. In addition to incorporating anthropological and sociological perspectives, Bowditch's theoretical approach makes use of concepts drawn from linguistics, deconstruction, and the work of Michel Foucault. She weaves together these ideas in an original approach to Horace's use of golden age imagery, his language concerning public gifts or munera, his metaphors of sacrifice, and the rhetoric of class and status found in these poems. Horace and the Gift Economy of Patronage represents an original approach to central issues and questions in the study of Latin literature, and sheds new light on our understanding of Roman society in general.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAncient & Classical. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aLowell Bowditch, Phebe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022603640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092589240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925892423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925892/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles